Media notes: Recorded between 2100 and 2126. Common Nighthawks are abundant at Altona Flat Rock, and there were typically 3-5 nighthawks visible in the general area of the microphone zeppelin at any given time.The loudest sounds in the recording, at the end of the first segment and start of the second segment, came when three individuals repeatedly circled around the zeppelin while chasing each other. These birds were approximately 1-2 meters from the zeppelin, and only 2-3 meters above the ground. It was light during the entire recording, and no moon was visible. Clear sky, calm, approximately 65°F. The habitat where the microphones were placed is an extensive cement area (the remnant of an old dam site) with small boulders and scattered shrubs and early-successional tree species.  Decoded MS Stereo recording. The microphones were located approximately two meters above the ground, with the zeppelin pointed upward. The two segments of this recording are nearly continuous, with just a brief pause between them to adjust the record level. Other Behaviors: Booms. Equipment Notes: Decoded MS Stereo recording. Microphones located approximately six feet above the ground, with the zeppelin pointed upward.

Observation Details: Late. This bird began flying along the dike and then over the water of Lake Josephine at or shortly before 5 p.m. Typical nighthawk shape with long and pointed wings showing bold white bars across the basal portion of the primaries. Overall cold gray and blackish; the underparts were barred with black; the upperwing showed a prominent and broad silvery-gray ulnar bar; the throat appeared grizzled white and gray/black and was not crisp and white (this and wing shape and tail feathers suggest an HY male); tail clearly showed white subterminal band at least on one side of rectrices. The wings appeared somewhat blunt for this species. The bird foraged over the lake, generally staying and only inches above the water. It occasionally rose steeply upward as if chasing something high over the lake. While gliding, it held wings above the body in a V with primaries angled or flexed slightly downward at the wrist. Quick and rapid turns.  Apparently juvenile male Common Nighthawks may molt their rectrices before completing migration. This bird exhibited an odd asymmetry, with the left outer rectrices apparently new and showing the white subterminal band of the male. The throat was typical of young bird, being grizzled. We also felt the wing tip was more blunt than expected on adults of this species. P10 is clearly shorter than P9 on this individual, this being a trait thought typical of Lesser Nighthawk. The cold coloration, shape of white wing bar (broadening to rear and squarish), and dark and virtually unbarred inner primaries all fit Common Nighthawk versus Lesser.

We walked the trail this morning about 6 am, right after sunrise when a Common Nighthawk flew from the dune area into the walking path and nestled, as if saying 'notice me and not my nest'! We saw no sign of a nest but the adult flew off the path and circled twice. A second one joined her and the two flew over three or four more times as we walked on. We saw the long pointed wings and distinctive beak. When flying we saw the white bar under each wing. Neither made a call. A photo will be added when I get home.

An incredible flock of daytime flying birds wheeling over the spillway traversed  by Test Station Road. White in wing was nearer “elbow” rather than near wingtip, and photos show the wings were pointed rather than rounded (as per lesser nighthawk). Back of camera Photos enclosed (will upload originals when we get home) and a poor iPhone video that attempted to capture the spectacle will be uploaded. Since the birds were flying rapidly to catch insects, the count was estimated by counting 5 birds and extrapolating to size of flock. The count is likely inaccurate since most of the flock was low over the spillway, but more birds were very high up in altitude.

Observation Details: Feeding 1806 hrs. Remained feeding immediate area until about 1840 hrs.  Fed alongside LAGUs for about 10 minutes

Late. This bird began flying along the dike and then over the water of Lake Josephine at or shortly before 5 p.m. Typical nighthawk shape with long and pointed wings showing bold white bars across the basal portion of the primaries. Overall cold gray and blackish; the underparts were barred with black; the upperwing showed a prominent and broad silvery-gray ulnar bar; the throat appeared grizzled white and gray/black and was not crisp and white (this and wing shape and tail feathers suggest an HY male); tail clearly showed white subterminal band at least on one side of rectrices. The wings appeared somewhat blunt for this species. The bird foraged over the lake, generally staying and only inches above the water. It occasionally rose steeply upward as if chasing something high over the lake. While gliding, it held wings above the body in a V with primaries angled or flexed slightly downward at the wrist. Quick and rapid turns.  Apparently juvenile male Common Nighthawks may molt their rectrices before completing migration. This bird exhibited an odd asymmetry, with the left outer rectrices apparently new and showing the white subterminal band of the male. The throat was typical of young bird, being grizzled. We also felt the wing tip was more blunt than expected on adults of this species. P10 is clearly shorter than P9 on this individual, this being a trait thought typical of Lesser Nighthawk. The cold coloration, shape of white wing bar (broadening to rear and squarish), and dark and virtually unbarred inner primaries all fit Common Nighthawk versus Lesser.

Pretty sure this is the common nighthawk that Tim et al. have reported from this area. Flushed from cottonwood grove. Mostly observed flying away or obscured behind trees, so no comment on the underwing in flight. Flight seemed obviously more direct than lesser, with less bounding style. Nabbed several photos of the bird perched on a high, conspicuous horizontal willow branch (an uncommon, though not impossible behavior for lesser). Primaries dark all the way down to the coverts, with no spotting apparent. White primary bar inconspicuous, but obviously lined up with the base (not the tip) of the tertials. Furthermore, p5 would be lined up directly behind the tertials in these photos, and the primary patches are clearly lined up well below p5, closer to where you would expect p4 or possibly even p3's tip. Also, white spot clearly on p6, which should never be the case for lesser nighthawk (only p7-p10). Appears to be a first year bird, which might explain the relatively short-winged look. Primaries appear relatively pointed. Overall tones are light gray, lacking obvious brown color. Not a great character, but this bird also lacks spotting on the greater coverts.

An incredible flock of daytime flying birds wheeling over the spillway traversed  by Test Station Road. White in wing was nearer “elbow” rather than near wingtip, and photos show the wings were pointed rather than rounded (as per lesser nighthawk). Back of camera Photos enclosed (will upload originals when we get home) and a poor iPhone video that attempted to capture the spectacle will be uploaded. Since the birds were flying rapidly to catch insects, the count was estimated by counting 5 birds and extrapolating to size of flock. The count is likely inaccurate since most of the flock was low over the spillway, but more birds were very high up in altitude.

Media notes: 3 Common Nighthawks: @200 PEENTs about 20 of which also had an unusual sound -- a "rattlle" -- (not found in ML, nor described in BNA, nor Pieplow's guide) 22 GROANs (three sets: 9, 8 and 5), and @ 18 FOOMS (aka wing booms).
Observation Details: 3 common nighthawks making @200 PEENT calls -- 20 of which include an unusual "rattle" sound (beginning at @50sec) not found in ML, nor described in BNA, nor Pieplow's guide. Described in Bent 1940. 2 possible but extremely brief recordings in Xeno-Canto) -- and @18 FOOMs (aka wing booms), 3 sets of GROANs (9 @4sec, 8 @3:39min, and 5 @ 6:30min)  I was at the Overlook (410 ft) on Schoodic Head (435 feet), so I was fairly level with them as they were flying/ foraging perhaps as low as 375 flying as high as 450 feet.  The first PEENT is heard within seconds of initiating recording. And though I was not aware of it at the time, there were GROAN sounds being made within 4 sec. The PEENTs with "rattles" started about @50 seconds into recording -- as they were flying in a formation, following each other very very closely -- one after the other. It seemed to me that were aware of me as they flew remarkably close -- especially during the first set of a dozen "rattles" -- which at one point was literally about to 10 feet away from me (perhaps I was being buzzed).  Other sound in background: lobster boats, waves on rocky coast occasional mosquitos  temperature 46 degrees partly cloudy skies  my original file: B03h56m39s16jun2017 this file: trimmed, high pass filter (250 Hz), normalized to -3 dB

First of spring for us, and perhaps the first record for California this spring. A high flying, pointy-winged nighthawk that we first identified in flight. Silent. Landed in Cottonwoods on the south side of the lake. Photographed in flight and on a branch. We spent the last couple days in Death Valley with lesser nighthawks and this one, by comparison, was much grayer overall with much longer outermost primaries giving a very pointy-winged appearance.

First bird showed up at 5:37 pm, shortly followed with others and then, 10-15 min later, with  60+ Lesser Nighthawks. Exact count, to the 5. Very difficult to get "to the bird" count. This was the highest count of CONIs I saw in the sky in once, all flying south. Indubitably more in the area. This evening was crazy abundant for nighthawks all over Kelowna. Smoke had just cleared and bugs were out in incredible abundance around watercourses, high overhead. I took a picture of a patch of the sky where a group of 15 nighthawks were hawking, and zoomed in; there were over 1000 bugs. This was a picture taken at 400mm. Phenomenal numbers - I have never seen this amount of nighthawks in my life, but there's no doubt why they were around, with the change of weather forcing bugs to fly in high density. Easy pickings for the goatsuckers!

As many as three flying around and calling. Two adults in particular were associating with one another and kept flying low over a certain area, even landing frequently in the pines. As I was setting up my scope to view and photograph one of them in a tree, another Nighthawk suddenly flushed from the ground nearly under my feet. This bird flew a short distance, barely getting off the ground, and proceeded to spread its wings in an exaggerated manner while croaking and holding open its bill--an apparent female using distraction techniques. I snapped a couple quick photos through my scope (without approaching) and then left them alone.

Observation Details: This is a conservative estimate. The first birds arrived at 18:26. About 20 minutes later, I realized that a large flock had arrived just outside my stationary field of view. These birds swirled over about a half square mile around my neighborhood - as far as I could see them in any direction - feeding and continuously being joined by more birds. By 19:40, all of the birds were no longer visible. Curiously, they did not disappear to the south, but rather to the southwest. Last year around this time, birds were observed moving more-or-less to the southwest without any feeding behavior that was sustained in one area.

Ejemplar localizado desde casa sobrevolando el Río Bernesga a la altura del puente de San Marcos. El observador desconoce la especie y baja a obtener unas fotografías que posteriormente cuelga en un grupo de facebook 'Aves de España y del Norte de África' el 27 de diciembre, pidiendo ayuda para saber la especie.   Es identificado por Andrés Rojas y remitido por Roberto Hurtado a Daniel Lopez (miembro del del CR-Seo). Finalmente tras varios días intentando contactar con el observador, se consiguen las fotos originales el 06/01/2021, confirmándose dicha observación y siendo homologada ese mismo día por el Comité de Rarezas. Se trata de la 3a homologada en España y 1a para CyL, emarcándose dicha cita en un buen otoño para la especie en Europa.

Adult female flushed from two nestlings in large area of slash. Female flushed downhill and began performing robust distraction display. Display involved landing in clear view with wings spread wide (showing bold white wing patches), gapping it’s mouth wide, and emitting a buggy, clicking alarm vocalization. Nestlings were small, covered in wispy, gray and brown down, and bunched tightly together. A small egg fragment lay nearby and was white mottled with grays and browns. The nest site was on a patch of earth with a dense layer of decomposing bark and other plant material. A small raspberry plant just south of nest site overarched the site and provided a small amount of shading.

The nighthawks seem to have anticipated this event and were ready to and did feast.

We walked the trail this morning about 6 am, right after sunrise when a Common Nighthawk flew from the dune area into the walking path and nestled, as if saying 'notice me and not my nest'! We saw no sign of a nest but the adult flew off the path and circled twice. A second one joined her and the two flew over three or four more times as we walked on. We saw the long pointed wings and distinctive beak. When flying we saw the white bar under each wing. Neither made a call. A photo will be added when I get home.

Locality: Milk River Bridge, West of Milk River

Observation Details: Continuing, day 6! I believe I was the 2nd person to lay eyes on it this evening. I was walking across the Riverdale Park grass from the parking lot toward the river, talking with D., when I saw a birder further ahead (an Asian gent, sorry I did not get your name) aim his camera at something above and behind us. I looked up and recognized the CONI immediately. It was silent, but I’d recently seen many in Texas. The bird had approached from the southwest and flew over Riverdale Park at 1710 (right on schedule) headed for its N. Lakeview Ave. bridge hunting ground. It must roost southwest of here. Out by the river, closer to the bridge, I stood with at least 18 other birders and enjoyed watching it fly up and down the river. A little west of the bridge it would turn back upstream, and then sometimes fly out of sight upstream, but always return to just west of the bridge and loop back around upstream. Always silent. Did not hear the distinctive “peent” call once. Captured it catching insects, and then missing (or changing its mind) on a dragonfly. Plenty insects at that altitude, apparently. A joy to watch, after the gamble I’d taken to drive up from far south and fight that traffic, on Day 6 even. Photos.

An incredible flock of daytime flying birds wheeling over the spillway traversed  by Test Station Road. White in wing was nearer “elbow” rather than near wingtip, and photos show the wings were pointed rather than rounded (as per lesser nighthawk). Back of camera Photos enclosed (will upload originals when we get home) and a poor iPhone video that attempted to capture the spectacle will be uploaded. Since the birds were flying rapidly to catch insects, the count was estimated by counting 5 birds and extrapolating to size of flock. The count is likely inaccurate since most of the flock was low over the spillway, but more birds were very high up in altitude.

Juvenile observed for almost half a day by many county and national birders perched on a garden fence off Springfield Road. A great find by the house owner, subsequently identified by Ian Lewington. Cryptic plumage, with large eyes, tiny bill and fine barring on chest and underparts. Large gape also observed twice as it opened its mouth. When it alighted at 7pm, flew high south towards the Downs. Fast, erratic flight, zig-zagging through the air, with long pointed wings and shallow forked tail.

Observation Details: Someone in the group of birders on Presque Isle this weekend found this day-roosting Common Nighthawk and word quickly spread.  Bird photographer, Bob Grubbs, led me to the general area, but we couldn't find it.  Ken and Nancy Andersen were nearby and were kind enough to walk back and show us the bird.  Dave and Shannon Thompson came by and were able to see it as was Mercedes Leofsky from the Purple Martin Conservation Association. Also coming by was Pittsburgh birder Michelle Kienholz.  I was fortunate to be able to photograph it using a tripod from a distance of about 100 feet.  It was resting in the sun on an oak tree limb that hung out over the water at the south end of the Cement Sidewalk Trail.  It was camouflaged, but its white throat was visible as was its white wing bar.  The bird also gave about 6 loud and characteristic “peent” calls while sitting lengthwise on the branch.  Several of us watched it for over an hour.  It did a 180 degree turn on the branch while preening.  Most of the time it slept with its eyes closed.

Depuis environ 2 semaines, les Engoulevents d'Amérique se regroupent dans le quartier et sont, soir après soir, de plus en plus nombreux, à virevolter à basse altitude à partir de l'heure du souper, de 17h à 19h.   Mais en ce vendredi 16 août, leur nombre grandissant vient probablement d'atteindre son apogée. En me déplaçant en auto, sur les 3 km du Boul. Vézina, j'en ai compté, juste en roulant, sans m'arrêter 58, et c'était seulement dans l'espace de ciel visible de chaque côté du boulevard, mais il y en avait beaucoup plus.   En arrivant, chez moi, il y en avait un autre groupe imposant volant au-dessus de la cours d'école et du quartier. J'en ai compté 47(+ 1 autre groupe de 10 un peu plus loin), et ce, toujours seulement dans l'espace de ciel qui m'était visible, mais encore une fois, il y en avait d'autres plus loin que je ne pouvais voir. J'estime le nombre à plus de 175 individus un peu partout au-dessus de la ville de Dolbeau, mais je vais me limiter à ce que j'ai compté.  Photo à venir !

This nighthawk flushed from in front of my car as I was parking. It flew around weakly and perched on a concrete barrier next to the road. In flight, it looked like a typical Common Nighthawk. It flushed again later and perched on a telephone line. The mottled throat and white edges to the primaries indicate that it's a juvenile bird. The length of the primaries, and the position of the white spots and lack of any buffy spotting on the primaries indicate that this is a Common Nighthawk, not a Lesser.

Breeding confirmed. Adult female with two chicks. Young were sitting under the female's fluffed breast. As one of the researchers (Michael Allen) was photographing the female at close range, she flushed from the chicks and performed the "broken-wing display," less than twenty feet away. The young were then subsequently photographed. The researchers have extensive experience with breeding CONI and their behavior at Lakehurst Naval Air Station. The nestlings will continue to be monitored and hopefully fledge successfully.

Observation Details: Some rufous highlights. This may be the bird that I flushed when I first arrived at Diamond Park.  It was resting on overhead cables and was more disturbed by my car when I started the ignition than when I walked up to it. It spread its wings as if to regain it's balance and then flew only a few feet away.  It stayed on those lines for almost an hour, so it was probably trying to sleep.  I know this because I left it for a while and then came back later, approaching from a different direction. It only flew off when I drove directly below it with my car.  Some of these photos were taken directly in front of the bird, so it was quite unconcerned about me although it did open it's eyes a bit.

Late. This bird began flying along the dike and then over the water of Lake Josephine at or shortly before 5 p.m. Typical nighthawk shape with long and pointed wings showing bold white bars across the basal portion of the primaries. Overall cold gray and blackish; the underparts were barred with black; the upperwing showed a prominent and broad silvery-gray ulnar bar; the throat appeared grizzled white and gray/black and was not crisp and white (this and wing shape and tail feathers suggest an HY male); tail clearly showed white subterminal band at least on one side of rectrices. The wings appeared somewhat blunt for this species. The bird foraged over the lake, generally staying and only inches above the water. It occasionally rose steeply upward as if chasing something high over the lake. While gliding, it held wings above the body in a V with primaries angled or flexed slightly downward at the wrist. Quick and rapid turns.  Apparently juvenile male Common Nighthawks may molt their rectrices before completing migration. This bird exhibited an odd asymmetry, with the left outer rectrices apparently new and showing the white subterminal band of the male. The throat was typical of young bird, being grizzled. We also felt the wing tip was more blunt than expected on adults of this species. P10 is clearly shorter than P9 on this individual, this being a trait thought typical of Lesser Nighthawk. The cold coloration, shape of white wing bar (broadening to rear and squarish), and dark and virtually unbarred inner primaries all fit Common Nighthawk versus Lesser.

Adult female flushed from two nestlings in large area of slash. Female flushed downhill and began performing robust distraction display. Display involved landing in clear view with wings spread wide (showing bold white wing patches), gapping it’s mouth wide, and emitting a buggy, clicking alarm vocalization. Nestlings were small, covered in wispy, gray and brown down, and bunched tightly together. A small egg fragment lay nearby and was white mottled with grays and browns. The nest site was on a patch of earth with a dense layer of decomposing bark and other plant material. A small raspberry plant just south of nest site overarched the site and provided a small amount of shading.

A first October record of this species for Chittenden County and only the 5th VT October record! Feeding actively above the I-89 south bound off ramp and park and ride traffic light and fields to the south. Initially seen while driving and I could not believe my eyes! I quickly pulled over, jumped out of my car, and began taking photos. Unmistakable flight pattern, silhouette, and white throat and wing patched, made the ID of CONI easy even from a long distance and without optics. I watched the bird feed around for about 3 minutes before I had to continue on my way. What a treat!

Conservative count. Evan and I stood in the middle of the Visitor Center field. We counted at least 500, counting by tens as well as we could, directly over the visitor center field, circling and feeding. At the same time we could see at least 200 flying over the Foothills Parkway and ridge to the east of the Visitor Center field.  There were hundreds that passed overhead going west to east after this, but we could not be sure that some of these were not part of that original 700. At 7:19, after the original group had dispersed over the eastern ridge, a new group of 156 flew over straight line west to east and higher up.

Observation Details: High count* Initially my thought was “oh nice a Woodcock!”. But once I got looks at a nighthawk flying over the point I remembered how they too are “peenters”. I walked down into a campsite to get a clear view of the lake and one by one more nighthawks appeared. Watching these birds bouncing around above the water, it felt like somewhat of a fallout; birds dropping out of the sky. These birds were all over the lake and although difficult to count, 55 was my best estimate. They have definitely arrived back in full force. An amazing experience to say the least!

Observation Details: I accidentally and unfortunately flushed this parent bird off of her nest and two chicks, which are in an opening not far removed from the trail. She flew out like a shot and performed a very effective distraction display to lure me away from the nest, flapping her wings and gaping. I took her photo and a quick photo of the young and then high-tailed it out of there in only a couple of minutes. I'm hiding the checklist for a few weeks to prevent enticing others to go look for her.

Media notes: Up to 3 Common Nighthawks: @300+ PEENTs, @24 FOOMS (aka wing booms), 12 GROANs,  9 DZIKs
Observation Details: At least 2 and possibly 3 Common Nighthawks making @300+ PEENT calls (once with a brief "rattle" at 2:10 min and @24 FOOMS (aka wing booms) in-flight, and courtship/mating calls made on the ground, including a set of 12 GROANs (at 9:57 min), wing flaps (at 10:04 min) at time of copulation (or attempted copulation) , and 9 DZIKs. Copulation (was witnessed 15-20 ft away from me.  Recorded at the Overlook (410 ft) on Schoodic Head (435 feet). Perhaps flying as low as 375 ft as high as 450 feet -- so I was recording as fairly level position with them on the rocky outcrop.  Other sound in background: lobster boats buoy bell surf on rocky coast  Temperature @50 degrees, and partly cloudy skies.  original file: B03h51m21s23jun2017y this file: trimmed, high pass filter (250 Hz), normalized to -3 dB

Nighthawks were dancing everywhere in the sky but then I saw two zoom down towards the ground quickly. They had not previously been doing this but immediately after they nosedived a crow gave a warning call. Immediately after this call ALL of them disappeared in less than 2 seconds. As the two birds that nose-dived flew back above tree line, I quickly realized that one was a peregrine.    The nighthawk got away safe & sound while the peregrine left to find dinner elsewhere. I hung around for another 10 minutes but no nighthawks returned.

As noted in the checklist's general comments, driving up County Road 402, about a quarter mile east of its junction with FM 2147 and CR 404, a nighthawk was seen flying fairly low over the road, heading northwest towards the pastureland a short distance off.  I only had a quick look at the bird, so pulled the car over as quickly as possible (narrow shoulder complicating things), hoping to get another glimpse of the nighthawk before it completely disappeared from sight. Though it had already gone beyond some trees, was pleasantly surprised to see the nighthawk, only about 20 seconds later, come flying right back over the road where it was first seen. Was even more surprised to see it fly into a live oak just above the road, and land on a large horizontal limb. Got good looks and photos (from a distance of maybe 25 yards). Appeared to be the much more expected (in this part of Texas) Common Nighthawk; the white wing patch could easily be seen on the folded wing of the bird, which crossed the primaries well short of the tertial tips, instead of directly below the tertial tips--or even slightly beyond--as in LENI.  Appeared to be a male based on the boldness [large size and brightness] of the white patch on the primaries, and also the boldness of the white throat patch.  Gray morph (as expected in this part of their range). No vocalizations were ever heard from the bird.  Although this would appear to be latish for a migrant, I have no idea if this general area might be potential breeding habitat for a CONI. Burnet County bird!

This nighthawk flushed from in front of my car as I was parking. It flew around weakly and perched on a concrete barrier next to the road. In flight, it looked like a typical Common Nighthawk. It flushed again later and perched on a telephone line. The mottled throat and white edges to the primaries indicate that it's a juvenile bird. The length of the primaries, and the position of the white spots and lack of any buffy spotting on the primaries indicate that this is a Common Nighthawk, not a Lesser.

Very early record for Massachusetts (previous earliest in e-bird is 4/28), and always rare along SE MA coast in spring.  Lesser Nighthawk's outer primary should be shorter than its 2nd to last primary, unlike this bird. Also, Lesser does not show the bold dark spotting on back.  Difficult to separate from Antillean Nighthawk without hearing calls, but cold gray plumage and wing structure suggests Common. Very long, pointed winged when seen in flight, and wings appea to project well past tail when sitting.

I was sitting on back patio and saw two nighthawks flying west over our house.  This has happened before but there is a narrow woods that runs north to south behind our development so once they flew west you don't see anything after that.  I walked out to front yard and didn't see them return.  After about 7-8 mins I figured out if I looked south closer to the end of our street which is higher than where I am I could see at least two flying back and forth east to west but only had a narrow view with all the trees in peoples backyards.  If I had been smart I would of walked down there but I didn't.  Then at 6:25pm I saw them one more time.  My pics were only taken later so they were much further away.  By the time you get the camera they don't come back over your house I guess.

Initially we saw two, then about 5 minutes later - eight came flying over and swooping over the two ponds. Within 10-15 minutes, there were over 20 and flying everywhere. Before leaving, we counted what we could without doubling and were able to count 34. We strongly believe there were more than 50. It was really cool to watch them fly around and forage. Sun was going down in the start of seeing them and it was getting pretty dark when we were leaving and the large amounts were flying around. Uploading some poor images taken to show ID.

Nighthawk migration continues. I had another good evening of Nighthawk migration over Elizabethton. My total for the evening was 268. I had two large groups, way up in the sky, over Watauga River and Holston Mountain (from Elizabethton) where they caught a thermal. When they finally broke out, they appeared to be heading in the direction of Watauga Lake / Butler. Had many smaller groups go over downtown. I did have one medium-sized group come from the west side of Elizabethton / East Johnson City direction

Nighthawks were dancing everywhere in the sky but then I saw two zoom down towards the ground quickly. They had not previously been doing this but immediately after they nosedived a crow gave a warning call. Immediately after this call ALL of them disappeared in less than 2 seconds. As the two birds that nose-dived flew back above tree line, I quickly realized that one was a peregrine.    The nighthawk got away safe & sound while the peregrine left to find dinner elsewhere. I hung around for another 10 minutes but no nighthawks returned.

3 babies are living on my front stoop, each night at dawn a 4th nighthawk arrives to fly and feed with the 3 little ones. I have pictures and video . They are brown and camouflage into the sidewalk.  They don't move even if you get super close. I believe all 3 are females as I don't see a white strip on neck. The white strip is on the under wing.  I am not about to identify if the 4th bird at night that arrives has a white strip or not.   This 4th bird is never present in the day time. I am unable to load the video so I took still shots of it.

This area is small and is surrounded with pasture lands, open wild grassland, and sage dessert.

Observation Details: I heard it first coming from N-S at the E end of my block.  It continued S to the E end of the property behind my house.  There it turned W and was flying over that property when I saw it; it was flying very high.  It continued W almost to S Ewing St calling.  Then, it turned N and flew over my street still calling.  As it flew N, it went out of my sight and I could no longer hear it. 10 minutes later I was still in my backyard when I heard it again coming from almost due-N of my house. So, I walked along the W side of my house to try to get more audio.  As I reached the front of my house a call came from just W of due-N, then almost immediately another call came from more E and N.  Possible pair but cannot confirm. One of them flew S. It flew over my street, practically over my head, over the S alley, and toward the S tree-line of the property behind me.  Then, the calls stopped.  Working on audios.

Observation Details: Desde que llegué al final del día a Bailadero del Diablo comencé a escuchar una vocalización en varias zonas que no conocía, las aves creo estaban escondidas en la vegetación o el suelo. Al regreso desde cascada El Perol en ruta a Perquin, vi un Rusty Sparrow en un poste de un cerco y me bajé del vehículo a ver si podía grabarlo. Vi tres nighthawks sobrevolando justo arriba y pensé en Lesser Nighthawk. De pronto al menos una de las aves comenzó a vocalizar con el mismo sonido que había escuchado repetidas veces y que no había podido ver. Le envié el sonido a biólogos Melvin Bonilla y Guillermo Funes. Melvin envió el audio a John van Dort y a Roselvy Juárez quienes confirmaron la especie. También Guillermo la confirmó. Se incluye audio grabado con sonido de motor del vehículo encendido. Sería el primer reporte con audio o foto para El Salvador en eBird.

Juvenile observed for almost half a day by many county and national birders perched on a garden fence off Springfield Road. A great find by the house owner, subsequently identified by Ian Lewington. Cryptic plumage, with large eyes, tiny bill and fine barring on chest and underparts. Large gape also observed twice as it opened its mouth. When it alighted at 7pm, flew high south towards the Downs. Fast, erratic flight, zig-zagging through the air, with long pointed wings and shallow forked tail.

A lifer! Seen roosting on a garden fence. Photo's that I took are attached below. I have also embedded a video that I recorded of the bird.   This species is very rare in the UK, and this bird was heavily twitched, apparently around 600 birders/twitchers came to pay homage on the day. It remained until approximately 7pm, when it flew. Unfortunately I was only able to watch the bird for around 45 minutes.   I observed the Nighthawk roosting, and was fortunate to see it preen itself, and shuffle from side to side every ten minutes or so. Locality: Head of the Meadow Beach, N. Truro
Observation Details: Moving WNW over dunes, beach and a few over the ocean. Birds were already in the air when we arrived at the National Park side at 17:15 hrs and we could easily have missed some passing through before that. These birds were counted over a 20 minute period in small groups of 5 - 15, most being relatively low over the dunes but also some moving over the pines at North of Highland Campground. Other closer individuals flew directly over the beach and we even had a few out over the open ocean. Almost all the movement was to the WNW with only a few singles heading ESE. I enjoyed the movement as I always do when watching nighthawks but hadn't given any real thought to the significance of the number relative to Cape Cod. It was a calm evening with little wind after a very blustery start to the day with winds in the NW quarter.

Observation Details: Photo

Pretty sure this is the common nighthawk that Tim et al. have reported from this area. Flushed from cottonwood grove. Mostly observed flying away or obscured behind trees, so no comment on the underwing in flight. Flight seemed obviously more direct than lesser, with less bounding style. Nabbed several photos of the bird perched on a high, conspicuous horizontal willow branch (an uncommon, though not impossible behavior for lesser). Primaries dark all the way down to the coverts, with no spotting apparent. White primary bar inconspicuous, but obviously lined up with the base (not the tip) of the tertials. Furthermore, p5 would be lined up directly behind the tertials in these photos, and the primary patches are clearly lined up well below p5, closer to where you would expect p4 or possibly even p3's tip. Also, white spot clearly on p6, which should never be the case for lesser nighthawk (only p7-p10). Appears to be a first year bird, which might explain the relatively short-winged look. Primaries appear relatively pointed. Overall tones are light gray, lacking obvious brown color. Not a great character, but this bird also lacks spotting on the greater coverts.

Someone in the group of birders on Presque Isle this weekend found this day-roosting Common Nighthawk and word quickly spread.  Bird photographer, Bob Grubbs, led me to the general area, but we couldn't find it.  Ken and Nancy Andersen were nearby and were kind enough to walk back and show us the bird.  Dave and Shannon Thompson came by and were able to see it as was Mercedes Leofsky from the Purple Martin Conservation Association. Also coming by was Pittsburgh birder Michelle Kienholz.  I was fortunate to be able to photograph it using a tripod from a distance of about 100 feet.  It was resting in the sun on an oak tree limb that hung out over the water at the south end of the Cement Sidewalk Trail.  It was camouflaged, but its white throat was visible as was its white wing bar.  The bird also gave about 6 loud and characteristic “peent” calls while sitting lengthwise on the branch.  Several of us watched it for over an hour.  It did a 180 degree turn on the branch while preening.  Most of the time it slept with its eyes closed.

Accurate count. As I was leaving at 9 pm (due to hearing some thunder with the heat lightning), a cluster of 4 flew on the east side of the monument followed almost immediately by a pair flying on the west side of the monument. All 6 were doing a passing from roughly south to north before breaking up and circling about again. The first one showed up at about 8:20 pm and the second and third one actually were darting around by the flag bearer statue at probably only 20 feet off the ground from what I could tell from my position down on the outer sidewalk (grounds close at 8pm). I had never seen them fly that low at this sight (wish I was up top in the actual monument area to have seen that). I  thought they initially might have been Hoary Bats due to their size and that is the normal flight area for bats, here, but then I could see from some of my photographs that the wings clearly had the vertical white wing bar on the outer area of the wings.

Observation Details: I refound the bird roosting at 7 AM at same location where Parke Custis first found it on 9/3. Hugh and I photographed it from a distance. It didn't flush. Still there now as we're leaving at 8:30.  Dom Mosur and Mark Eaton out as well.   From parking lot at entrance to Gleneagles Golf Course, walk across street to utility pole with big gray utility box on it. There is an area of cleared vegetation directly behind it. The nighthawk is roosting on ground next to a green plastic bottle. We agree this is a Common Nighthawk.  Please be respectful of the bird and do not approach too closely. You can see and photograph it from a distance.  Thanks to Parke for reporting this. Great find!

Dom Mosur and Mark Eaton out as well.   From parking lot at entrance to Gleneagles Golf Course, walk across street to utility pole with big gray utility box on it. There is an area of cleared vegetation directly behind it. The nighthawk is roosting on ground next to a green plastic bottle. We agree this is a Common Nighthawk.  Please be respectful of the bird and do not approach too closely. You can see and photograph it from a distance.  Thanks to Parke for reporting this. Great find!

A lone CONI appeared at about 9:10 pm flying high over the monument. It never dipped below the top of the monument. Like last night, there were lots of bats in the air (10+) that smaller groups of them were flying mid-height on the monument. Individual bats would also trail very closely to the CONI and the CONI flew to elude them with some alternating turns. At times there was a light drizzle that I had hoped would drop the CONI's flight closer to the base but that never happened. Possibly the large number of bats were also influencing the CONI's altitude.

Depuis environ 2 semaines, les Engoulevents d'Amérique se regroupent dans le quartier et sont, soir après soir, de plus en plus nombreux, à virevolter à basse altitude à partir de l'heure du souper, de 17h à 19h.   Mais en ce vendredi 16 août, leur nombre grandissant vient probablement d'atteindre son apogée. En me déplaçant en auto, sur les 3 km du Boul. Vézina, j'en ai compté, juste en roulant, sans m'arrêter 58, et c'était seulement dans l'espace de ciel visible de chaque côté du boulevard, mais il y en avait beaucoup plus.   En arrivant, chez moi, il y en avait un autre groupe imposant volant au-dessus de la cours d'école et du quartier. J'en ai compté 47(+ 1 autre groupe de 10 un peu plus loin), et ce, toujours seulement dans l'espace de ciel qui m'était visible, mais encore une fois, il y en avait d'autres plus loin que je ne pouvais voir. J'estime le nombre à plus de 175 individus un peu partout au-dessus de la ville de Dolbeau, mais je vais me limiter à ce que j'ai compté.  Photo à venir !

Locality: Grasslands NP--West Block (General area, use more specific hotspots)
Observation Details: Sooooo cool. The bird was nestled in a tree right outside our tee pee where we spent the night in  the park all alone:) With the mosquitoes and all the other bugs.

The bird, which Dominic Halas had flushed earlier was now perched precariously and crosswise on a utility line about six metres off the ground. It wobbled in the strong SW winds. Later it flew a couple of times to a horizontal willow branch. Of course, this was a very late record (latest Hamilton record is November 9, 1983) and we wanted to ensure that it was not a Lesser Nighthawk. The bird was a Common Nighthawk: its wings would have extended beyond the tail  (except that the tail was lowered for balance in this case); the long wings meant that the white patches in the wings were not as far out on the wing as in LENH; there were not buffy spots proximal to the white patch as there would be in LENH.  Photos attached.

Observation Details: Continuing, day 6! I believe I was the 2nd person to lay eyes on it this evening. I was walking across the Riverdale Park grass from the parking lot toward the river, talking with D., when I saw a birder further ahead (an Asian gent, sorry I did not get your name) aim his camera at something above and behind us. I looked up and recognized the CONI immediately. It was silent, but I’d recently seen many in Texas. The bird had approached from the southwest and flew over Riverdale Park at 1710 (right on schedule) headed for its N. Lakeview Ave. bridge hunting ground. It must roost southwest of here. Out by the river, closer to the bridge, I stood with at least 18 other birders and enjoyed watching it fly up and down the river. A little west of the bridge it would turn back upstream, and then sometimes fly out of sight upstream, but always return to just west of the bridge and loop back around upstream. Always silent. Did not hear the distinctive “peent” call once. Captured it catching insects, and then missing (or changing its mind) on a dragonfly. Plenty insects at that altitude, apparently. A joy to watch, after the gamble I’d taken to drive up from far south and fight that traffic, on Day 6 even. Photos.

Rare in Alaska. Five birds began vocalizing (peents and booms) and flying around the gravel bar at 950pm continuing for more than an hour until we left the area. All birds giving frequent nasal 'peent' calls and a few giving courtship dives. Deep wingbeats, white bar across base of primaries.

Locality: Capital Plaza Shopping ctr. (Purple Martin roost), Austin

Observation Details: Chased down a report from Roy Churchwell who had posted a sighting on Facebook's Alaska Rare Bird Alert page on 6-23-22 in the area of Timberwolf Lane (off Montana Creek Rd.). At 10pm as we looped around this neighborhood on foot, we heard distant but distinctive “peent” calls coming from the direction of the nearby gravel pit to the northwest. Sure enough, the bird flew directly overhead the Timberwolf Ln. neighborhood giving good looks and close audio. Medium sized long-winged nightjar with white bars toward the end of the wings and a white throat. Photos and audio to be uploaded.

*Very High Count | first spotted the group at 6:40. Most of the action was in the first 35 minutes, with a much slower trickle in the last few minutes, although the slow and steady stream that lasted for well over 45 minutes. Counted individually as they passed by, large spacing between individual birds made it easy to count them all. Seen by 3 observers. Large group that trickled by over the river between South Portland and Portland heading west towards the Western Prom. I couldn't get any photos that captured the size of the group since individuals were usually relatively spaced out. Amazing!

This is a nighthawk, but I'm not sure how it can be ID'd with certainty as a Common. I assume that's what it is, but how do we know? Three pix of the bird facing right; eventually, it turned around, so two pix of of it facing left too. EDIT: I just read about comparing the placement of the white patch on the sitting bird relative to the longest tertials. Cool field mark! Never knew that one. So this is a COMMON NIGHTHAWK, unless someone protests.  FURTHER EDIT: CHANGE TO COMMON NIGHTHAWK, PER GUIDANCE OF EBIRD REVIEWER TONY LEUKERING.

Nighthawks were dancing everywhere in the sky but then I saw two zoom down towards the ground quickly. They had not previously been doing this but immediately after they nosedived a crow gave a warning call. Immediately after this call ALL of them disappeared in less than 2 seconds. As the two birds that nose-dived flew back above tree line, I quickly realized that one was a peregrine.    The nighthawk got away safe & sound while the peregrine left to find dinner elsewhere. I hung around for another 10 minutes but no nighthawks returned.

Observation Details: 1x1 count of silent nighthawks with longer more angular wings than Lesser Nighthawk and white wing bars more proximal to body than seen in Lesser Nighthawk. They came in as a feeding flock after sunset, insect eating over the water. The ongoing mayfly outbreak is the probable reason why they are still present and surviving, while most of their associates should be in South America by now. Dark o’clock photos taken, with all photos being taken after sunset, and the last one taken in near complete dark conditions. Digital photography is amazing and not too many years ago, documentary photos such as these would have been impossible.

Background Species: Cardinalis cardinalis [cardinalis Group] -- Northern Cardinal (Common); Thryothorus ludovicianus [ludovicianus Group] -- Carolina Wren (Northern); Zenaida macroura -- Mourning Dove; Agelaius phoeniceus [phoeniceus Group] -- Red-winged Blackbird (Red-winged)

Observation Details: Robin and I were returning from dinner just a little before 6 pm when we approached the entrance to Del Webb's Bridgewater community here in Brownton (Ha, auto-correct just corrected "Brownstown"  because it thought I was going to mention my home here at Brownton Abbey!). Anyways, I saw a flock of swirling birds that I initially thought were swallows, then I realized that they were pretty large. Purple Martins? It took my head a few seconds to recalibrate and realize that I was seeing a flock of low-flying Common Night Hawks! They were flying over the ponds and feeding on insect swarms in the late afternoon sun! I dropped Robin off (at Brownton) and grabbed the camera and headed back to spend the next 20 minutes or so shooting off ~2000 frames trying to capture these nightjars while they dodged photons coming from my camera. My arms were tired trying to track them while maintaining focus. It felt like someone was throwing a knuckleball not knowing which way it'll dip. But, I managed a few keepers, including some with their mouths wide open and ready to snatch flying insects. A nice way to come home. I took Asia out in the yard a while later and saw the flock return right over the house. This time they were much higher, but I was able to count 60 birds!

cool encounter! saw medium sized bird hovering very high while I was at the clearing south of the railroad bridge. Its flight style was very hawk-like hovering around and not direct, turning and making some loops in the sky while gradually moving east. Interestingly, last time I spotted nighthawks in the same area they were also flying east, so maybe they go in that direction for the night? (not really sure what is over there but it definitely is interesting), however last time I saw them they flew by quite fast and quite low (ok not as fast as canada geese or ducks for example but the flight was relatively direct without turning around like a hawk like this one). initially while seen in the viewfinder it was so far away, I couldn't quite make it out what it was and thought it might be some kind of accipiter or even a merlin or kestrel ( like some kind of falcon because of thing wings + short head and long tail), but I was just guessing. It stayed in my vision for about 30 seconds before it went far west of neshaminy creek and disappeared from sight, only identified it after reviewing photos. Second time seeing it so far!
